trans-unit.source: Represents the collection of selected items in the <xref href="System.Windows.Forms.ListBox"></xref>.
The <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.SelectedObjectCollection> class stores the selected items in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox>.
The items stored in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.SelectedObjectCollection> are items contained within the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.ObjectCollection> class.
The <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.ObjectCollection> class stores all items displayed in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox>.

The following table is an example of how the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.ObjectCollection> stores the items of the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox> as well as their selection states within an example <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox>.
Index
Item
Selection state within the ListBox
object1
Unselected
object2
Selected
object3
Unselected
object4
Selected
object5
Selected

Based on the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.ObjectCollection> demonstrated in the previous table, the following table demonstrates how the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.SelectedObjectCollection> would appear.
Index
Selected item from ObjectCollection
object2
object4
object5
You can use the properties and methods of this class to perform a variety of tasks with the collection.

The <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.SelectedObjectCollection.Contains%2A> method enables you to determine whether an item from the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.ObjectCollection> class is a member of the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.SelectedObjectCollection>.

Once you know that the item is located within the collection, you can use the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.SelectedIndexCollection.IndexOf%2A> method to determine where a specific item within the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.ObjectCollection> for the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox> is stored within the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.SelectedObjectCollection>.
Initializes a new instance of the <xref href="System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.SelectedObjectCollection"></xref> class.
An instance of this class cannot be created without associating it with a <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox> control.
A <xref href="System.Windows.Forms.ListBox"></xref> representing the owner of the collection.
Adds an item to the list of selected items for a <xref href="System.Windows.Forms.ListBox"></xref>.
An object representing the item to add to the collection of selected items.
Removes all items from the collection of selected items.
Determines whether the specified item is located within the collection.

The <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.SelectedObjectCollection.Contains%2A> method enables you to determine whether an item from the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.ObjectCollection> class is a member of the selected items stored in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.SelectedObjectCollection>.
You can use this to determine if a specific item in a multiple-selection <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox> is selected.
An object representing the item to locate in the collection.
`true` if the specified item is located in the collection; otherwise, `false`.
Copies the entire collection into an existing array at a specified location within the array.
You can use this method to combine the selected items from multiple collections into a single array.
An <xref href="System.Array"></xref> representing the array to copy the contents of the collection to.
The location within the destination array to copy the items from the collection to.
Gets the number of items in the collection.
This property enables you to determine the number of selected items in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox>.
You can then use this value when looping through the values of the collection and you need to provide a number of iterations to perform the loop.

Unless the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.SelectionMode%2A> property of the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox> is set to `SelectionMode.MultiSimple` or `SelectionMode.MultiExtended`, this property always returns a value of zero (0) or one (1) depending on whether you have a selected item.
The number of items in the collection.
Returns an enumerator that can be used to iterate through the selected item collection.
An <xref href="System.Collections.IEnumerator"></xref> that represents the item collection.
Returns the index within the collection of the specified item.

Once you know that an item is located within the collection (using the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.SelectedObjectCollection.Contains%2A> method), you can use the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.SelectedObjectCollection.IndexOf%2A> method to determine where a specific item within the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.ObjectCollection> for the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox> is stored within the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.SelectedObjectCollection>.
An object representing the item to locate in the collection.
The zero-based index of the item in the collection; otherwise, -1.
Gets a value indicating whether the collection is read-only.
This property is always `true` for this collection.
`true` if the collection is read-only; otherwise, `false`.
Gets the item at the specified index within the collection.
This indexer enables you to get a specific item from the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.SelectedObjectCollection>.

The item stored in this collection is an item within the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox.ObjectCollection> of the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox> that represents a selected item in the <xref:System.Windows.Forms.ListBox>.
The index of the item in the collection to retrieve.
An object representing the item located at the specified index within the collection.
The index parameter is less than zero or greater than or equal to the value of the property of the class.
Removes the specified object from the collection of selected items.
